"Please!" Elwynn queen implored, "Don't send her away! She's just a child!" The Ice King sat on his throne, gazing down at his wife, royal advisors standing by her side. The queen had given birth to a girl. At the mere thought of it, the Ice King's brow furrowed.
The infant girl resembles her mother: she has pale blue eyes, snow-white hair, and a few strands of blue hair woven into it. The Ice King believes that having a daughter will make him seem weak. After all, he only had sons before this.
"You have two choices: either kill the child or leave her in the wilderness. Elwin, this is your punishment." He spat out her name with venom, as if it were poison. He always did.
The Frost Kingdom was not always a single kingdom. It was once divided into two parts, the northern and southern regions. The northern region established a non-magical kingdom, while the southern region was a kingdom filled with magical powers. Due to the northern region's greed, the two kingdoms broke out into endless wars, until the southern region proposed a ceasefire.
At that time, the South was already in despair, and the members of the royal family were willing to sacrifice everything to prevent this bloody conflict. They proposed that the only princess be married to the North, becoming the queen of the North and giving birth to a son as the future king. Afterwards, the South would merge with the North and establish a unified kingdom. The North accepted this proposal, and Princess Elvyn married Prince Akur.
"Please, my king, for the sake of my child's safety, you can do anything to me, lock me up, exile me, even kill me." Queen Elwes begged, holding her child tightly in her arms.
The king looked down at his queen with disgust in his eyes, perhaps, just perhaps, he would have a little pity for her. After all, this woman had been by his side for 22 years, caring for him in his darkest moments, bringing him children to raise.
"Okay. The child can live in the palace." Hearing the Ice King's words, the queen relaxed. "But, however, you will be executed."
The royal advisor and Queen Elwynn both displayed expressions of shock. She slowly lowered her head, looking at the floor. "Yes, my king," she curtsied.
The Ice King ordered royal advisors to bring the queen's daughter to an empty room in Elven. After that, he ordered guards to take Elven to a public execution ground where everyone in the city could see.
As the sentries led her to the scaffold, citizens saw their only queen – and their kindest queen – about to be executed, and they were very angry. Some people cried, some shouted and tried to attack the sentries, while others wondered why this had to happen; but they all had the same question.
"Let her go!"
"Why are they treating her like that?"
As Elwin approached the wooden pillar, the most feared person in the kingdom appeared. He was the executioner of burning at the stake. The former queen, Elwin, was to be burned alive. No one deserves to be burned at the stake, even a criminal. In the Frost Kingdom, burning at the stake is the cruelest punishment.
Erlvin was bound to a wooden pole; the King began to tell of how the Queen had betrayed them all. The people of Niflheim refused to believe and would never accept the King's words. Then the executioner lit the pole, a single tear rolled down the face of the former Queen.
"Carly, stay alive!" The life of Queen Elwin thus came to an end.
The grand hall was eerily silent.
In the south wing of the icy palace, a never-ending "tick-tock" sound was coming from the room on the far left. Servants who had passed by the door were always curious about what was inside, but they were too afraid to approach. The maids would whisper to each other in the hallways, spreading all sorts of rumors. Some believed that the deceased wife of the Ice King, Elwyn, was imprisoned in that very room, waiting to be released.
They made a huge mistake. Ephraim walked along, thinking, while the servants walked back and forth along the wall, whispering to each other. They had no idea what was inside.
Of course, there were many rumors about him because he was the only one allowed to enter the room.
Knocking gently on the door. "Miss Carly, are you in?" Avery whispered, addressing the intricately decorated door, adorned with snowflakes and a crown motif, emblematic of the royal family.
He doesn't know if she will let him in this time, which is definitely different from before. I still have the bruises from last time. Avery couldn't help but laugh as he recalled the incident. At the time, Carly threw a book at him, but immediately apologized when she realized who it was.
A faint noise came from the room, as if it was telling her she couldn't go anywhere else, and she was stuck there.
"Can I come in?" Avery asked, not forgetting the consequences of his last uninvited visit.
A faint creak echoed through the room again, as if it was inviting him to come in. Avery felt a chill run down his spine, unsure if it was the cold or the voice. Although he had been there for many years, the sound from the room still made him feel a little strange.
I've come in," Avery said, slowly opening the door. By normal standards, the scene in the room was quite unusual, but it was also to be expected. The room was filled with paper. Books were scattered all over the floor, and a desk was broken, and there were many ice sculptures in the room. The room had no windows, and almost no light. The room was also colder than other parts of the palace (which told a lot). The room looked like it had been hit by a blizzard, everything was in disarray.
The girl in the room curled up on the bed, wrapped in a blanket, and was reading a notebook. A small lantern lit up the room.
"What notebook are you reading?" Avery sat beside Carly's bed, asking.
